<subSubSection id="6DB72FD25C4AAC27F8E3FD0D3305FC34" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="25127C595C4AAC27F8E3FD0D3305FC34" blockId="23.[192,1441,675,987]" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis id="17D9A04B5C4AAC27F8E3FD0D3607FD54" bold="true" box="[192,332,675,699]" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Comment.</emphasis>
Unfortunately specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="E2AD07DA5C4AAC27FABCFD0D3424FD54" authorityName="Clarke &amp; Flora &amp; Fauna &amp; Casilla &amp; de &amp; Sierra &amp; Bolivia" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Penaherrera-Leiva and Tavakilian" baseAuthorityYear="2003" box="[671,879,675,699]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Charisia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bleuzeni">
<emphasis id="17D9A04B5C4AAC27FABCFD0D3424FD54" box="[671,879,675,699]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Charisia bleuzeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(originally described from a single female) were not available for study (but excellent photographs of both sexes provided enough detail for those characters mentioned in the text). The species could probably be placed in a genus of its own. It has a general resemblance to 
<taxonomicName id="E2AD07DA5C4AAC27F95AFCAD352EFCF4" authorityName="Gounelle" authorityYear="1911" box="[377,613,771,795]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Charisia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melanaria">
<emphasis id="17D9A04B5C4AAC27F95AFCAD352EFCF4" box="[377,613,771,795]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Charisia melanaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs from all the species of 
<taxonomicName id="E2AD07DA5C4AAC27FBD4FCAD332AFCF4" authorityName="Champion" authorityYear="1892" box="[1015,1121,771,795]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Charisia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17D9A04B5C4AAC27FBD4FCAD332AFCF4" box="[1015,1121,771,795]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Charisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the well developed tufts of setae on the metatibia, and the shape of the male’s abdomen. It cannot be placed in 
<taxonomicName id="E2AD07DA5C4AAC27FCF5FC8D321DFCD4" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1870" box="[1238,1366,803,827]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Epimelitta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis id="17D9A04B5C4AAC27FCF5FC8D321DFCD4" box="[1238,1366,803,827]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Epimelitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="0CEA1D305C4AAC27FD7FFC8A32EBFCD4" box="[1372,1440,804,827]" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
because the forebody is distinctly shorter than abdomen; the prothorax is widest near middle; the integument is black; and the body pubescence is not orange in color. Nor can it be placed in 
<taxonomicName id="E2AD07DA5C4AAC27FD24FCCD32EBFC94" authorityName="Clarke &amp; Flora &amp; Fauna &amp; Casilla &amp; de &amp; Sierra &amp; Bolivia" authorityYear="2016" box="[1287,1440,867,891]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Exepimelitta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17D9A04B5C4AAC27FD24FCCD32EBFC94" box="[1287,1440,867,891]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Exepimelitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because the pronotum is subquadrate, not strongly transverse; the general body pubescence is reduced, the pronotum lacking the dense, long setae of the transverse depression, the urosternites lacking hairy tufts; and the apex of the metafemora lack the characteristic fascia of white hairs.
</paragraph>
